Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell[TextData[{
 "PRIMAT ",
 StyleBox["(PRImordial MATter)",
  FontSlant->"Italic"]
}], "Title",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.693919653589431*^9, 3.693919659924049*^9}, {
  3.6983760912093763`*^9, 3.698376102376957*^9}, {3.698376280421982*^9, 
  3.698376318688294*^9}, {3.7165781799616003`*^9, 3.716578187967279*^9}, {
  3.725263124679394*^9, 
  3.725263130980825*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"627138b0-9782-4525-b17a-\
52f25ee8d089"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "PRIMAT is a ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " code which computes the abundances of elements at the end of the big-bang \
nucleosynthesis (BBN).\nIt can be downloaded by registering at ",
 ButtonBox["http://www2.iap.fr/users/pitrou/primat.htm\n\n",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["http://www2.iap.fr/users/pitrou/primat.htm"], None},
  ButtonNote->"http://www2.iap.fr/users/pitrou/primat.htm"],
 "Version 0.3.0  (01/10/2024)"
}], "Text",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8965445909946737`*^9, 3.8965446171550293`*^9}, {
  3.89654518726621*^9, 3.896545187396744*^9}, {3.934952140860058*^9, 
  3.934952146551703*^9}, {3.935980632875593*^9, 3.935980635506379*^9}, {
  3.936395833848961*^9, 3.936395838069528*^9}, {3.936668300947833*^9, 
  3.9366683032932367`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"293bc3e1-8858-4a16-b7f5-\
97e5a6b3c62f"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Information", "Chapter",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7003895925681963`*^9, 
  3.700389600642549*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e3f5c546-1df9-453b-abe8-\
576ac563211c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Short description", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.715914818121237*^9, 3.715914822518201*^9}, {
  3.715959059432568*^9, 
  3.715959060895135*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a090d2d0-bce3-4c6d-b20e-\
ecb6f51e9781"],

Cell[TextData[{
 " *The implementation follows the presentation of the companion paper \
Pitrou, Coc, Uzan, Vangioni, ",
 ButtonBox["Physics Reports, 04, (2018) 005",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/\
S0370157318301054"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0370157318301054"],\

 ". \n   All equation numbers, when non specified, refer to this companion \
paper, in its arXiv version (",
 ButtonBox["arXiv:1801.08023",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/1801.08023"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://arxiv.org/abs/1801.08023"],
 ").\n\n *It is based on a previous Fortran code written by Alain Coc.\n  \n \
*The user can modify several parameters which are in the preamble of the code \
:\n \n   a) The nuclear reaction rates involved in the nuclear reaction \
network are tabulated in an external file which can be easily modified.\n   \
b) The corrections to the weak-interaction reactions (n + \[Nu] <-> ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["p", "+"], "+", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["e", "-"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "67f59420-a931-4d68-829c-8c5b8025f045"],
 " and its related reactions), can be turned on and off with booleans. \n     \
 The details of these corrections are given in the companion paper.\n   c) \
Cosmological parameters, that is essentially the number of baryons ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    SubscriptBox["\[CapitalOmega]", "b"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2123f87d-3841-436e-a923-fd0a9f8f92bd"],
 ") and the number of neutrino generations ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["N", "\[Nu]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b32f93c5-b7db-49b6-96c2-72b2c2813cb3"],
 " can also be modified.\n   \n *The numerical integration is performed in \
two steps. First the cosmology and the thermodynamics of the plasma are \
solved, \n   and then the nuclear reactions are computed, the backreaction of \
the latter on the former being negligible (see companion paper).\n   \n *The \
results are given as a set of interpolating functions of time for the \
abundances of individual species. \n   If one is interested in final \
abundances only, these are also directly accessible by evaluating these \
functions at final time.\n\n  *A very basic Monte-Carlo exploration of \
uncertainties is provided at the end of the code. It is used in associated \
example notebooks located in the \[OpenCurlyQuote]Example\[CloseCurlyQuote] \
folder.\n   For each reaction, an uncertainty factor variance is provided and \
it is possible to run the code with these uncertainty parameters taking \
random values according to the variances (see [Coc et al. 2014]). A \
parallelization is possible for this Monte-Carlo exploration and the analysis \
of the results can be output in an external file and analyzed separately.\n   \
\n   *Several examples and applications are gathered in the \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]Examples\[CloseCurlyQuote] folder.\n   \n   *Neutrino \
decoupling is handled using output files generated by the (non-public) Python \
code NEVO [",
 ButtonBox["Froustey et al. 2020",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://arxiv.org/abs/2008.01074"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://arxiv.org/abs/2008.01074"],
 "].\n   \n   *An option allows to use only a reduced network of equations \
(weak interactions and 12 nuclear reactions), resulting in much faster \
results, though slightly different for Li7 abundances."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.935567600711*^9, 3.9355676007139473`*^9}, {
  3.9355677061644897`*^9, 3.935567706167366*^9}, {3.935567743500054*^9, 
  3.935567744936063*^9}, {3.937019952346328*^9, 
  3.937019953589983*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"33cc7cc4-6b7f-4361-a429-\
0e8442a75513"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\n",
 StyleBox["*** BASIC USAGE ***",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "\n\n*In the Evaluation menu, select \[OpenCurlyQuote]Evaluate notebook\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]. If asked the question \[OpenCurlyQuote]evaluate \
initialization cells first ?\[CloseCurlyQuote], answer No. \nThen Mathematica \
proceeds in evaluating all cells, in order, and it should reach the end of \
the notebook (with the plots and results) in less than one minute.\n\n*If the \
user erases the precomputed weak rates which are precomputed and stored in \
the \[OpenCurlyQuote]Interpolation\[CloseCurlyQuote] folder, or asks for \
these rates to be re-precomputed, this can take considerably longer, \
typically one hour."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.935567751878262*^9, 3.935567752217424*^9}, {
  3.936166671694188*^9, 
  3.936166686315489*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"97219a76-28e3-4926-bf89-\
a3be90289a43"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "*Furthermore, when ",
 StyleBox["PRIMAT-Main.nb",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontWeight->"Regular"],
 " (this notebook) is opened and saved in Mathematica, the cells which are \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]initialization cells\[CloseCurlyQuote] are saved into the \
file ",
 StyleBox["PRIMAT-Main.m",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontWeight->"Regular"],
 ".\nThis ",
 StyleBox["*.m",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontWeight->"Regular"],
 " file contains all the important definitions, functions and variables which \
can be loaded from another notebook to perform BBN computations and analysis \
of results.\nThe 'Examples' Folder contains several typical applications \
which work exactly like that. First it loads all necessary definitions stored \
in ",
 StyleBox["PRIMAT-Main.m",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontWeight->"Regular"],
 " and then it performs a few useful computations for each selected example."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.948212658969298*^9, 
  3.9482126643284397`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7cfab1de-409c-4ac1-aab8-\
f69dc338c225"]
}, Open  ]],

