Cell["Monte-Carlo uncertainty estimation options", "Text",
 CellDingbat->"\[FilledSquare]",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.715920372139921*^9, 3.715920409490917*^9}, {
  3.715920440783332*^9, 3.715920444857109*^9}, {3.7226089346025248`*^9, 
  3.7226089490163107`*^9}},
 FontSize->16,
 FontVariations->{
 "Underline"->True},ExpressionUUID->"433350d1-4509-4811-99a4-824888ecdc33"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"$RandomNuclearRates", "=", "False"}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"$MaxVariationRate", "=", "1000"}], ";"}]}], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.700386367200856*^9, 3.700386367369774*^9}, 
   3.719928709272653*^9},
 CellLabel->
  "In[1766]:=",ExpressionUUID->"c9af897a-6950-4c04-a340-60240444ff6e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If ",
 StyleBox["$RandomNuclearRates",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontSize->13,
  FontWeight->"SemiBold"],
 " is True, then each time we build the equations of the nuclear network, we \
generate rates with a log normal distribution according to the \
\[OpenCurlyQuote]f\[CloseCurlyQuote] specified (see Eq. 4.5 of [Coc et al. \
2014] for definition of f). \nWe limit f to the values ",
 StyleBox["1/$MaxVariationRate < f < $MaxVariationRate",
  FontFamily->"Source Sans Code",
  FontWeight->"Regular"],
 " ."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.948213727050686*^9, 
  3.9482137287512407`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"34270de5-5d0b-4541-9d65-\
193eed29ab62"],

Cell["Rescaling of some rates", "Text",
 CellDingbat->"\[FilledSquare]",
 FontSize->18,
 FontVariations->{
 "Underline"->True},ExpressionUUID->"5c8f2821-589c-434d-8770-ae61148fcfdd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "It is possible to rescale some rates by choosing their rescaling factor \
below. First, the option ",
 StyleBox["$RescaleSomeRates",
  FontFamily->"Source Code Pro",
  FontSize->13,
  FontWeight->"SemiBold"],
 " must be set to True otherwise the rescaling factors are ignored."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c75a20b2-9425-4874-b471-48ed88507806"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"$RescaleSomeRates", "=", "False"}], ";"}]], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellLabel->
  "In[1768]:=",ExpressionUUID->"61ecf06d-f3b7-41cc-ac86-5654650b1638"],

Cell["\<\
For each reaction whose rate we want to rescale, we need to know the exact \
name of the reaction. The names of reactions are collected in tables below in \
the core of the notebook. For a reaction of the type a + b -> c + d, the name \
is \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]abTOcd\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]. However one needs \
to know the order of the initial particles and of the final particles, and to \
put correctly the photons if they appear. Hence it is recommended not to \
guess the name of the rate, but to properly read it from the Tables below \
located in the section \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Collecting all reaction rates\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote].
For instance the reaction He3 + t > He4 + d  (we use d for H2 and t for H3 \
and a for He4) has name He3tTOHe4d. The factor to modify it is therefore \
He3tTOHe4dFactor.

As an example, we show how to introduce a rescaling factor for the d + p -> \
He3 + \[Gamma],  d + d -> He3 + n, and d + d -> H3 + p  reactions hereafter. 
If we want to vary other rates, one needs only to set the numerical value of \
their associated factors .\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0e0504fd-3dfe-441d-80c4-b86a41425abd"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"If", "[", 
   RowBox[{"$RescaleSomeRates", ",", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"dpTOHe3gFactor", "=", "1"}], ";", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
     RowBox[{"ddTOHe3nFactor", "=", "1"}], ";", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
     RowBox[{"ddTOtpFactor", "=", "1"}], ";"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   "]"}], ";"}]], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellLabel->
  "In[1769]:=",ExpressionUUID->"087b005f-a214-4197-9c4c-f84f084f14fc"],

Cell["\<\
Note that this procedure is only valid for variation of rates which are given \
as tables in the external file. If the user wants to vary a rate whose form \
is analytic, it is sufficient to add a factor \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]ReactionFactor\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] in the \
definition of the analytic forward rate (forward[T9_]:= ....). It is then \
advised to write here (so that all modifications can be turned on and off \
without forgetting that some rates have been modified)

If[$RescaleSomeRates,
ReactionFactor=100;,
ReactionFactor=1;
]

We recall that the syntax for If/then/else is

If[Condition, 
commandtrue;,
commandfalse;
]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5d518a9b-e42d-4e58-9bd0-3170b0b424cb"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["QED corrections (pair production) to nuclear rates",
 FontSize->16,
 FontVariations->{"Underline"->True}]], "Text",
 CellDingbat->
  "\[FilledSquare]",ExpressionUUID->"980c1b3c-7aeb-435c-843f-7657a9adf011"],

Cell["\<\
If this options is set to True, then we rescale some rates due to pair \
productions in the final state. 
See [Pitrou&Pospelov 2020].\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d3fdf3c8-d514-4165-bbe6-4259088c094a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"$NuclearRatesQEDCorrections", "=", "True"}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", " ", 
   RowBox[{"recommended", " ", "value", " ", "is", " ", "True"}], " ", 
   "*)"}]}]], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.861260253121438*^9, 3.861260254666264*^9}, {
  3.861260469458742*^9, 3.861260476730362*^9}, {3.861260697494587*^9, 
  3.861260698077643*^9}, {3.861261699162174*^9, 3.861261699648961*^9}},
 CellLabel->
  "In[1770]:=",ExpressionUUID->"7d65655c-57e4-4fc4-bbfe-6b6436293106"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Weak rates options", "Subsection",
 InitializationCell->
  True,ExpressionUUID->"90f9ae96-7414-42b5-85be-2a318b460a79"],

Cell["\<\
Since the weak interaction rates, that is the rates of weak reactions of the \
type n + \[Nu] <-> p + e and associated reactions, depend only on temperature, 
these can be computed once and for all so as to explore the dependence in \
cosmological parameters or other parameters. 
  
If $RecomputeWeakRates is set to True, the code recomputes the weak rates. 
Otherwise it reads them from files previously stored. If the file does not \
exist, it recomputes the rates.

If $ParallelWeakRates=True this is done using parallelization over the \
various CPUs that Mathematica can detect (be aware that when $NEVO=TRue , it \
slows things done because of badly sharing memory. I cannot find the reason.)\
\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.935543627331623*^9, 3.935543643983611*^9}, {
  3.936404628014121*^9, 
  3.936404646494323*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6b12bf47-f342-4594-a77b-\
70f24963cab3"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"$RecomputeWeakRates", "=", "False"}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"$ParallelWeakRates", "=", "False"}], ";"}]}], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->CompressedData["
1:eJwdxU8oQ3EcAPBnB8myLTTFvAxFlEX5/6/fQSEO3kjJn7WM8WJi4eBP2XDQ
5OoimoN20Pb2JhlTzMHk7wlbDpt/sRc5LNHk9/sePn2UWgOjE1EURWPk5/66
mVRnGL2dq+FAiZtOw3P0JRxcbxhU4HcW41myb5KxzbnCqHW5H5ZznUn8fhjd
9A3AK3PvHnJHZRTeYyeHJrxhxPzMwyu9OaNkSloLj05bN7z47xQnnCg/s5/g
szKSHWSztLE7FCOg3scuOJLu0JGN2X+w5iKO72gR0OtFHazdvvaT/dYQPFJj
u9Pg7zVuuC2rPtfICIganobFq3QfmW8vhsuqo4UmvIuRFZElPT/H5IUliZcc
rMiUmfHjnAou+IocLOLp/FgP+URU5dvCKxKa4SIqj21QC8i+UwUfuW9vr/AL
0SdYGzjNv8Fv8gH4N9GgCuFXx2Zh1nIo+sD/bV3DcZzVIm4TkOfJCU/tPpjk
eKP/E7YrX0r1egGtsU3l5H8VhPde
  "],
 CellLabel->
  "In[1771]:=",ExpressionUUID->"32192ced-29d4-4cb7-94d4-d4b4d5c80535"],

Cell["\<\
There are several booleans corresponding to the different types of \
corrections which can be considered in these weak rates. 
The name of the file used for storing the rates is built out of these \
booleans. 

Since the corrections do not add linearly, there are in principle many \
choices of corrections, but the only meaningful
choices are those without any corrections and those with all corrections \
included. 
Or maybe those with just one correction added, so as to check its amplitude.\
\>", "Text",
 InitializationCell->
  True,ExpressionUUID->"128f1039-5a8b-4833-a915-c9fa30b5d8a0"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"$RadiativeCorrections", "=", "True"}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Recommended", " ", "True"}], "*)"}], 
  "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"$ResummedLogsRadiativeCorrections", "=", "True"}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Recommended", " ", "True"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"$RelativisticFermiFunction", "=", "True"}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Recommended", " ", "True"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellLabel->
  "In[1773]:=",ExpressionUUID->"a611470b-64ec-481a-91c1-0f369bdca23a"],

Cell["\<\
1) If $RadiativeCorrections is set to True, we use Coulomb and radiative \
corrections (see section III.E of companion paper. The corrections are \
implemented in Eqs. 101 and 104.).
If $ResummedLogsRadiativeCorrections is set to True we use Eq. 15 of \
[Czarnecki et al 2004] which amounts to resumming some higher order radiative \
corrections, and this is also Eq. B35 of the companion paper.

If $ResummedLogsRadiativeCorrections is False we use simply Eq. 7 of the same \
reference, which corresponds to Eq. 103 and B30 of the companion paper.
If $RelativisticFermiFunction is True we use the relativistic Fermi function \
(Eq. 5 in [Ivanov 2012]), which corresponds to Eq. 100 of the companion \
paper. Otherwise we use the standard non-relativistic Fermi function, given \
by Eq. 99 of the companion paper.\
\>", "Text",
 InitializationCell->
  True,ExpressionUUID->"03a9bddb-fbde-42a0-8cac-fa6554e242e4"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"$RadiativeThermal", "=", "True"}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
    "Recommended", " ", "True", " ", "but", " ", "it", " ", "is", " ", "much",
      " ", 
     RowBox[{"slower", ".", " ", "Since"}], " ", "the", " ", "modification", 
     " ", "brought", " ", "by", " ", "these", " ", "corrections", " ", "is", 
     " ", "very", " ", "small"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"setting", " ", "False", " ", "is", " ", 
     RowBox[{"acceptable", "."}]}]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"$CorrectionBremsstrahlung", "=", "True"}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Recommended", " ", "True"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 InitializationCell->True,
